<li id="cite_note-79"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-79">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">For examples, see Johnson and Ryan, <i>Sexuality in Greek and Roman Society</i>, p. 116, note 4, quoting a fragment from <a href="/wiki/Solon" title="Solon">Solon</a>: "a man falls in love with a youth in the full-flower of boy-love / possessed of desire-enhancing thighs and a honey-sweet mouth"; Nussbaum, <i>Sex and Social Justice</i>, p. 450, note 48, quoting a fragment of the lost <i>Myrmidons</i> of <a href="/wiki/Aeschylus" title="Aeschylus">Aeschylus</a> in which <a href="/wiki/Achilles" title="Achilles">Achilles</a> mourns the dead <a href="/wiki/Patroclus" title="Patroclus">Patroclus</a>, their "many kisses", and the "god-fearing converse with your thighs".</span>
